WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.800 --> 00:00:05.290
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:18.750 --> 00:00:20.110
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Hello,
my name is David Plylar

00:00:20.110 --> 00:00:22.810
and I'm a music specialist
at the Library of Congress.

00:00:22.810 --> 00:00:28.050
It is my great pleasure to be here
today with Paul Lewis, pianist,

00:00:28.050 --> 00:00:30.090
who is playing at the library.

00:00:30.090 --> 00:00:35.740
Mr. Lewis, you have a long and
distinguished career already

00:00:36.950 --> 00:00:40.170
and your focus during
that time has been largely

00:00:40.170 --> 00:00:43.200
on two composers, Beethoven
and Schubert.

00:00:43.200 --> 00:00:47.400
Your work with Beethoven involved
recordings and performances

00:00:47.400 --> 00:00:50.700
of all 32 piano sonatas,
as well as the concerto

00:00:50.700 --> 00:00:52.970
and the Diabelli variations.

00:00:52.970 --> 00:00:58.630
Can you just say a bit about
what that journey was like?

00:00:58.630 --> 00:01:02.030
&gt;&gt; PAUL LEWIS: I wish I could say
something intelligent about it,

00:01:02.030 --> 00:01:04.460
but the thing is it feels
like it's still ongoing.

00:01:04.460 --> 00:01:09.730
It's hard to say what the journey
feels like really when you are kind

00:01:09.730 --> 00:01:12.930
of still in the middle of it
in a sense, because it's hard

00:01:12.930 --> 00:01:20.030
to step away from it and look at
it with some kind of detachment.

00:01:20.030 --> 00:01:23.540
It's -- the two years I spent
with the Beethoven sonatas,

00:01:23.540 --> 00:01:28.920
like the last two years I spent
with mature Schubert piano music,

00:01:28.920 --> 00:01:33.560
has just been the most incredible
time really musically, you know.

00:01:33.560 --> 00:01:38.130
I mean, this is music that I feel
it's the core of my repertoire.

00:01:38.130 --> 00:01:44.250 position:56%
I'm lucky enough to be able to spend
this time concentrating, you know,

00:01:44.250 --> 00:01:48.640
specifically on these two composers
or to have periods where I do that.

00:01:48.640 --> 00:01:52.540
Some people say to
me, "Don't you find

00:01:52.540 --> 00:01:54.300
after a while you want
a bit more variety?"

00:01:54.300 --> 00:01:56.780 position:56%
But I think this is the whole point.

00:01:56.780 --> 00:02:02.380
The range within these two
composers is really something

00:02:02.380 --> 00:02:03.680
quite extraordinary.

00:02:03.680 --> 00:02:08.930
And the longer you spend with them
the more you realize what they

00:02:08.930 --> 00:02:10.230
span really.

00:02:10.230 --> 00:02:13.390
The -- it's difficult to describe.

00:02:13.390 --> 00:02:19.160
The longer you spend with the music
the more you realize how much you

00:02:19.160 --> 00:02:20.460
don't know.

00:02:20.460 --> 00:02:23.770
So, the end of this two years,
for instance now with Schubert,

00:02:23.770 --> 00:02:26.590
it feels like I'm just
starting in a way.

00:02:26.590 --> 00:02:31.010
I'm just sort of getting into
it in a way, after two years.

00:02:31.010 --> 00:02:36.780
And it will feel strange to
move on and do something else.

00:02:36.780 --> 00:02:41.200
But in another sense it's
necessary to do that as well.

00:02:41.200 --> 00:02:42.650
&gt;&gt; DAVID PLYLAR: Well, in --

00:02:42.650 --> 00:02:45.780
before you did this massive
Beethoven project you had been

00:02:45.780 --> 00:02:47.260
involved with Schubert before.

00:02:47.260 --> 00:02:50.760
You had produced a few
recordings at that time.

00:02:50.760 --> 00:02:53.680
So, in a sense you are kind of
living that what you just said,

00:02:53.680 --> 00:02:56.470
that you are coming
back to it again.

00:02:56.470 --> 00:03:02.530 position:56%
How -- do you find that your playing
is informed in a different way

00:03:02.530 --> 00:03:04.850
after that Beethoven
project, of Schubert?

00:03:04.850 --> 00:03:09.770
&gt;&gt; PAUL LEWIS: I think Beethoven's
a great teacher in many ways.

00:03:09.770 --> 00:03:15.650
Again, it's difficult
to step away from it

00:03:15.650 --> 00:03:18.870
and see how your playing
has changed.

00:03:18.870 --> 00:03:23.170
Only -- I don't listen
to my own recordings.

00:03:23.170 --> 00:03:27.370
It's just too difficult to
listen to one's own recordings.

00:03:27.370 --> 00:03:32.510
But next month I'm rerecording
the C minor Schubert sonata,

00:03:32.510 --> 00:03:37.280
which was on my first
CD 12 years ago.

00:03:37.280 --> 00:03:41.320
So, I did listen to that and it's
quite astonishing how much it

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:42.620
has changed.

00:03:42.620 --> 00:03:47.760
You don't notice it much in the
process, but when you listen back,

00:03:47.760 --> 00:03:50.640
yeah, lots of things have changed.

00:03:50.640 --> 00:03:56.350
It's all about balance really, it's
all about trying to find a balance

00:03:56.350 --> 00:03:59.600
that you think makes sense and
that you think is convincing

00:03:59.600 --> 00:04:02.320
of all the different
elements within these pieces.

00:04:02.320 --> 00:04:06.620
And I suppose, you know, as
you play them for years and go

00:04:06.620 --> 00:04:11.100 position:56%
through your life living with them,
that balance is constantly changing.

00:04:11.100 --> 00:04:13.260
&gt;&gt; DAVID PLYLAR: Almost like
a lifelong gestation process.

00:04:13.260 --> 00:04:14.730
&gt;&gt; PAUL LEWIS: Exactly.

00:04:14.730 --> 00:04:16.030
Yeah.

00:04:16.030 --> 00:04:18.810
&gt;&gt; DAVID PLYLAR: That makes
me think of the, you know,

00:04:18.810 --> 00:04:23.720
comparing Beethoven and Schubert,
contemporaries in many respects.

00:04:23.720 --> 00:04:26.080
Almost exactly, except for
Schubert's short lifespan,

00:04:26.080 --> 00:04:28.850
towards the ends of the lives.

00:04:28.850 --> 00:04:33.340
Schubert is often compared to
Beethoven in ways or looking

00:04:33.340 --> 00:04:37.310
for influences in Schubert of
Beethoven on him and other things

00:04:37.310 --> 00:04:41.390
like that, perhaps unfairly when
he has such an individual voice

00:04:41.390 --> 00:04:46.870
and I think I -- or maybe you
could speak to that a little bit.

00:04:46.870 --> 00:04:50.950
What is unique about his --
say with the piano sonatas,

00:04:50.950 --> 00:04:52.920
versus the Beethoven sonatas?

00:04:52.920 --> 00:04:56.070
&gt;&gt; PAUL LEWIS: yeah, I think
it's true, the comparison

00:04:56.070 --> 00:05:00.870
with Beethoven is often made,
but I think if you're looking

00:05:00.870 --> 00:05:05.170
to compare Schubert with Beethoven
in that sense you have Beethoven

00:05:05.170 --> 00:05:08.200
as the standard by which
Schubert is judged.

00:05:08.200 --> 00:05:11.060
Schubert comes out second, not
because the music is inferior

00:05:11.060 --> 00:05:14.060
in any way, because
it's not Beethoven,

00:05:14.060 --> 00:05:15.460
it's completely different.

00:05:15.460 --> 00:05:16.760
And the more time I spend with both

00:05:16.760 --> 00:05:19.170
of these composures the more
I see the differences rather

00:05:19.170 --> 00:05:20.470
than the similarities.

00:05:20.470 --> 00:05:24.520
And I've always felt that
one of the big differences

00:05:24.520 --> 00:05:29.910
between these two composures that
Beethoven often seems to resolve

00:05:29.910 --> 00:05:33.410
in a way the end of a
great work of Beethoven.

00:05:33.410 --> 00:05:36.190
You feel that you've
arrived somewhere.

00:05:36.190 --> 00:05:40.110
You are at the end of a journey
that's a sense of resolution.

00:05:40.110 --> 00:05:43.100
Whereas with Schubert
it's very rarely the case.

00:05:43.100 --> 00:05:46.260
I don't think Schubert
tries to do that at all.

00:05:46.260 --> 00:05:49.100
Quite often you end up
with more questions hanging

00:05:49.100 --> 00:05:50.990
in the air than you started with.

00:05:50.990 --> 00:05:54.800
And I think that's really
fundamental to the nature

00:05:54.800 --> 00:05:57.680
of the music of these
two composures.

00:05:57.680 --> 00:06:02.330 position:56%
And that even for that soul reason
it's very difficult to compare them.

00:06:02.330 --> 00:06:06.290
I think you have to judge
them by their own standards.

00:06:06.290 --> 00:06:10.550
&gt;&gt; DAVID PLYLAR: Well, no,
that makes sense to me.

00:06:10.550 --> 00:06:14.390
With Schubert's publication
history, post --

00:06:14.390 --> 00:06:19.200 position:56%
or not to get into it explicitly --
many of his works were not published

00:06:19.200 --> 00:06:23.960
in his lifetime and so, the process
of dissemination was delayed,

00:06:23.960 --> 00:06:26.910
whereas with Beethoven it
was a different situation.

00:06:26.910 --> 00:06:31.800
With the piano sonatas, even
into this century, you know,

00:06:31.800 --> 00:06:34.820
you don't see them as
often on as piano recitals

00:06:34.820 --> 00:06:36.360
as one might like to see them.

00:06:36.360 --> 00:06:41.860
Where do you see that now in terms
of his recognition among your peers

00:06:41.860 --> 00:06:44.940
or as pianists looking
at Schubert's work?

00:06:44.940 --> 00:06:46.240
&gt;&gt; PAUL LEWIS: I think
that there's --

00:06:46.240 --> 00:06:47.900
for sure there's been a shift

00:06:47.900 --> 00:06:51.550
in the way we perceive
Schubert over the years.

00:06:51.550 --> 00:06:57.060
At 100 years ago these Schubert
sonatas were still very much

00:06:57.060 --> 00:06:59.920
neglected, they were
largely unknown.

00:06:59.920 --> 00:07:05.320 position:56%
I think it was Schnabel that brought
them into the concert hall and then

00:07:05.320 --> 00:07:12.370
after that Alfred Brendel
later in the 60s and so on.

00:07:12.370 --> 00:07:16.800
But even then I so -- it's
only some of the later sonatas

00:07:16.800 --> 00:07:21.360
that really became I suppose
you could say mainstream.

00:07:21.360 --> 00:07:24.930
A lot of the others
remained neglected.

00:07:24.930 --> 00:07:27.750
I think it's different now.

00:07:27.750 --> 00:07:33.200
I think we see Schubert, the
composer, in a different light.

00:07:33.200 --> 00:07:37.490
We see that he is not this
traditional Gamucklick [phonetic

00:07:37.490 --> 00:07:42.130
spelling] cozy composer of salon
pieces, over the, you know,

00:07:42.130 --> 00:07:47.150
the miniatures that he wrote,
of course, still great music.

00:07:47.150 --> 00:07:51.700
But the large scales, the
sonatas and the symphonies

00:07:51.700 --> 00:07:55.470
and the bigger pieces of
chamber music, I just --

00:07:55.470 --> 00:07:59.070
it's just wonderful, great music.

00:07:59.070 --> 00:08:04.030
We see that he's in
many ways the darkness

00:08:04.030 --> 00:08:06.840
of Schubert I think has come more

00:08:06.840 --> 00:08:10.060
into our understanding
of him as a composer.

00:08:10.060 --> 00:08:15.350 position:56%
Perhaps there was also a time
recently where he was seen primarily

00:08:15.350 --> 00:08:18.380
as a dark tormented composer
and I think that's come

00:08:18.380 --> 00:08:20.020
into a different kind
of balance now.

00:08:20.020 --> 00:08:24.440
So, yeah, 200 years later
we're still finding a way

00:08:24.440 --> 00:08:25.850
to understand Schubert.

00:08:25.850 --> 00:08:30.940
And it's fascinating the
way that it goes, I think.

00:08:30.940 --> 00:08:32.760
&gt;&gt; DAVID PLYLAR: Well, I
thought we could take a look

00:08:32.760 --> 00:08:34.160
at a few manuscripts.

00:08:34.160 --> 00:08:39.290
We've got a couple
of small items here.

00:08:39.290 --> 00:08:43.180
The first being the
autographed manuscript

00:08:43.180 --> 00:08:46.970
of Beethoven's Opus
109, E major sonata.

00:08:52.130 --> 00:08:57.220
When one encounters -- this is my
first time seeing this manuscript

00:08:57.220 --> 00:09:00.460
myself and it's --
there's a certain sense

00:09:00.460 --> 00:09:04.180
in which one feels a certain --

00:09:04.180 --> 00:09:07.240
you can see kind of the process
of composition unfolding in front

00:09:07.240 --> 00:09:09.440 position:56%
of you, literally with certain types

00:09:09.440 --> 00:09:13.590
of amendments, edits,
things like that.

00:09:13.590 --> 00:09:17.770
You having performed and
recorded this particular piece,

00:09:17.770 --> 00:09:20.590
do you have any initial
reactions on seeing it?

00:09:20.590 --> 00:09:22.240
We can take a look
at other pieces too.

00:09:22.240 --> 00:09:24.160
&gt;&gt; PAUL LEWIS: Yeah, I'm
just overwhelmed basically.

00:09:24.160 --> 00:09:25.980
I saw this for the first time.

00:09:25.980 --> 00:09:29.320
I knew I was going to see it, but
then when you see it you think,

00:09:29.320 --> 00:09:31.660
"This is it, this is
the real thing."

00:09:31.660 --> 00:09:35.140
There's just absolutely
astonishing really.

00:09:35.140 --> 00:09:36.440
I mean, it comes alive.

00:09:36.440 --> 00:09:40.280
There's such a life to it.

00:09:40.280 --> 00:09:45.000
Which it's hard to describe and
it's hard to grasp in a way.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:50.010
I just noticed here in the
first movement there was a bar

00:09:50.010 --> 00:09:51.460
in the middle of a long line.

00:09:51.460 --> 00:09:56.300
He appears to have added a
bar almost as an afterthought,

00:09:56.300 --> 00:09:59.250
which changes the sense
of that line.

00:09:59.250 --> 00:10:00.950
It's, you know, of course,

00:10:00.950 --> 00:10:04.740
only seeing the manuscript you
would realize things like this.

00:10:04.740 --> 00:10:07.640
It's really incredible.

00:10:07.640 --> 00:10:08.940
&gt;&gt; DAVID PLYLAR: One other
thing that starts to come

00:10:08.940 --> 00:10:13.470
up as you look are the
different types of markings,

00:10:13.470 --> 00:10:16.650
the different sizes of, you
have your forte written out

00:10:16.650 --> 00:10:20.460
and very clearly here
just to make sure

00:10:20.460 --> 00:10:21.760
that you know what is
supposed to happen.

00:10:21.760 --> 00:10:24.060
&gt;&gt; PAUL LEWIS: Yeah.

00:10:26.490 --> 00:10:34.380 position:56%
Yeah, later with -- later Beethoven
he became more and more prescriptive

00:10:34.380 --> 00:10:42.330
in the way he wrote and what
one can easily see that here.

00:10:42.330 --> 00:10:47.780
It's actually a lot more organized
than I thought it was going to be.

00:10:47.780 --> 00:10:49.210
It's clearer.

00:10:49.210 --> 00:10:52.170
Because I have some --
I've seen some manuscripts

00:10:52.170 --> 00:10:56.530 position:56%
of middle period Beethoven, which
are incredibly chaotic and they sort

00:10:56.530 --> 00:11:00.930
of scream at you in
a way off the page.

00:11:00.930 --> 00:11:06.270
And this somehow more detailed
and there's a clarity to this.

00:11:08.720 --> 00:11:11.180
&gt;&gt; DAVID PLYLAR: Now, with
this particular sonata,

00:11:11.180 --> 00:11:19.840
it features the variation set at
the end, this is how -- this is --

00:11:19.840 --> 00:11:21.950
maybe you're thinking of
this in relation to Schubert

00:11:21.950 --> 00:11:25.560 position:56%
where you had mentioned earlier that
Beethoven tends to take the material

00:11:25.560 --> 00:11:29.290
and win at the end
in some way, to some.

00:11:29.290 --> 00:11:31.600
This particular piece has
a different sort of ending

00:11:31.600 --> 00:11:37.960
where the triumph is almost in
a return or a sense of calmness.

00:11:37.960 --> 00:11:39.260
I don't know.

00:11:39.260 --> 00:11:40.560
&gt;&gt; PAUL LEWIS: Yeah.

00:11:40.560 --> 00:11:42.800 position:56%
&gt;&gt; DAVID PLYLAR: But maybe that's an
example of just the kind of breadth

00:11:42.800 --> 00:11:44.800
that is there in the
Beethoven sonatas.

00:11:44.800 --> 00:11:46.100
&gt;&gt; PAUL LEWIS: Yeah.

00:11:46.100 --> 00:11:48.700
I think the feeling of resolution
comes out in different ways

00:11:48.700 --> 00:11:51.590
in different periods of
Beethoven's compositions.

00:11:51.590 --> 00:11:53.150
In the middle period,
of course, they --

00:11:53.150 --> 00:11:56.340 position:56%
you often get this sense of triumph.

00:11:56.340 --> 00:11:58.780
In the later period I
think it's different.

00:11:58.780 --> 00:12:04.200
There's an intimate
introspective quality to this.

00:12:04.200 --> 00:12:05.970
But you still feel that --

00:12:05.970 --> 00:12:07.610
especially at the end

00:12:07.610 --> 00:12:11.280
of the variation movement
there is a sense of resolution.

00:12:11.280 --> 00:12:14.930
You feel that it doesn't
need to carry on.

00:12:14.930 --> 00:12:17.290
It's come to a conclusion.

00:12:17.290 --> 00:12:21.510
