00:28:45.840 --> 00:28:48.740
Yeah, so it's a mixed bag.

00:28:48.740 --> 00:28:54.110
In the next few years I'm
also coming back to Haydn

00:28:54.110 --> 00:28:58.790
and I'm considering maybe doing
a sort of Haydn project, because,

00:28:58.790 --> 00:29:03.620
I mean, this wonderful
rich music and, you know,

00:29:03.620 --> 00:29:08.130
there's a lot of Haydn which I
also feel can often be overlooked.

00:29:08.130 --> 00:29:09.430
&gt;&gt; DAVID PLYLAR: Absolutely.

00:29:09.430 --> 00:29:12.560
One doesn't find it represented
in recital programs very often.

00:29:12.560 --> 00:29:13.860
&gt;&gt; PAUL LEWIS: Yeah.

00:29:13.860 --> 00:29:15.160
&gt;&gt; DAVID PLYLAR: For sure.

00:29:15.160 --> 00:29:16.460 position:56%
&gt;&gt; PAUL LEWIS: Maybe just one or two

00:29:16.460 --> 00:29:18.370
of the well-known sonatas,
but outside that...

00:29:18.370 --> 00:29:19.890
So, that's something.

00:29:19.890 --> 00:29:22.790
I'm also considering the picking

00:29:22.790 --> 00:29:28.050
up the Roibcur [phonetic spelling]
sonata, which of course he was one

00:29:28.050 --> 00:29:32.550
of Liszt's favorite pupils,
died when he was in his 20s,

00:29:32.550 --> 00:29:36.790
left just a handful of pieces.

00:29:36.790 --> 00:29:39.380
There's the organ, there's
the great organ work,

00:29:39.380 --> 00:29:42.390
there's this piano sonata.

00:29:42.390 --> 00:29:43.690
&gt;&gt; DAVID PLYLAR: Should we mention

00:29:43.690 --> 00:29:45.690
that sonata I believe is
written just a few years

00:29:45.690 --> 00:29:47.300
after Liszt's B minor sonata.

00:29:47.300 --> 00:29:48.600
&gt;&gt; PAUL LEWIS: Yeah.

00:29:48.600 --> 00:29:50.080
&gt;&gt; DAVID PLYLAR: It's the
work of B flat minor, I think.

00:29:50.080 --> 00:29:51.500
&gt;&gt; PAUL LEWIS: that's right.

00:29:51.500 --> 00:29:54.970
And there are similiarities
for sure.

00:29:54.970 --> 00:29:56.650
It's about the same length.

00:29:56.650 --> 00:30:00.340
It's a similar kind
of form that it has.

00:30:00.340 --> 00:30:03.340
In fact, the original end
to the B minor sonata,

00:30:03.340 --> 00:30:08.110
which was this very
strong fortissimo ending.

00:30:08.110 --> 00:30:11.700
The Roibcur has that
and you feel it.

00:30:11.700 --> 00:30:13.790
It's sort of modeled a little
bit on the Liszt sonata,

00:30:13.790 --> 00:30:16.960
but with the original end.

00:30:16.960 --> 00:30:23.210
But it's also it's very much
its own original thing as well.

00:30:23.210 --> 00:30:29.100
And it's just a wonderfully
heartfelt work and I feel

00:30:29.100 --> 00:30:31.290
that that clearly is something

00:30:31.290 --> 00:30:34.340
that doesn't get played
very often and deserves to.

00:30:34.340 --> 00:30:37.200
&gt;&gt; DAVID PLYLAR: One gets a
sense of, even though many

00:30:37.200 --> 00:30:42.600
of these composers, Roibcur
aside, perhaps are well-known

00:30:42.600 --> 00:30:46.800
to audiences generally, there's
a sense of advocacy in your work

00:30:46.800 --> 00:30:49.700
that comes through when
you're playing, I believe,

00:30:49.700 --> 00:30:54.640
in a sense of really communing with
the work and getting to know it

00:30:54.640 --> 00:30:56.370
and that's something

00:30:56.370 --> 00:30:59.200
that we definitely very much
appreciate about your work.

00:30:59.200 --> 00:31:01.610
